                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1373">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/147.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-23T11:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 23, 1912—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The citations from Moore, in Department’s March 20, 7 p.m., seem to deny
                    responsibility of a government for damages to foreigners by mob violence unless
                    it can be shown that the government had not exercised due diligence. Your
                    telegram February 12, 5 p.m., which I consider a contingent and pending
                    instruction, indicates that under stated conditions you would hold the Mexican
                    Government liable for damages without regard to the amount of diligence
                    exercised. Does the Department hold that action contemplated in its February 12,
                    5 p.m., changes the status of American claims?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
